Invitation to be Part of a Research Study

You are invited to be part of a research study. Before you decide if you would like to participate, it is important for you to understand why the research is being done and what it will involve. Please take time to read the following information carefully. Feel free to ask if anything is not clear in this consent form.


Your Participation in this Study is Voluntary 


It is totally up to you to decide to be in this research study. Participating in this study is voluntary. Even if you decide to be part of the study now, you may change your mind and stop at any time. You do not have to answer any questions you do not want to answer. Your decision not to take part or to withdraw will involve no penalty or loss of benefits to which you are otherwise entitled. 


What is the study about and why are we doing it?

The purpose of the study is to administer online surveys to project participants such as researchers, ethicists, lawyers, and persons with lived experience of mental health conditions to gain information about trends of neuroscience data sharing.    


What will happen if you take part in this study?


If you agree to take part in this study, you will be asked to complete an online survey via Google forms. 


The survey will include questions about how to create, access, store, and share data. The questions are divided into 5 categories: your professional experience, the technological aspects of data governance, the legal aspects of data governance, the ethical aspects of data governance, and the lived experience aspects of data governance. There will be a combination of multiple choice and short answer questions.


Your participation in this study will last up to 1 hour. Approximately 80 individuals will participate in this study. 


What risks and discomforts might you experience from being in this study?


There are some risks and discomforts you might experience from being in this study. 


You may be uncomfortable while answering the survey/interview questions. You can skip any questions that make you uncomfortable or that you do not want to answer. 


Participation in research might involve some loss of privacy. There is small risk that someone outside the research study could see and misuse information about you. More information about how we will protect your information to reduce this risk can be found below.


You may learn things about yourself that you did not know before and that could affect how you think about yourself.



How could you benefit from this study?


There is no guarantee that you will receive any benefits from being in this study. However, possible benefits include an increased awareness of the data governance landscape in your geographical region. We hope the information learned from this study will provide more information about the unique data governance strengths and weaknesses in your geographical regions.


How will information about you be protected?


UT Austin has established secure research databases and computer systems to store information and to help with monitoring and oversight of research. Your information may be kept in these databases but are only accessible to individuals working on this study or authorized individuals who have access for specific research related tasks. 

Identifiable information in these databases is not released outside of UT Austin unless stated in this consent or required by law. Although results of this research may be presented at meetings or in publications, identifiable personal information about participants will not be disclosed. 

Personal information about you might be shared with or copied by authorized representatives from the following organizations for the purposes of managing, monitoring, and overseeing this study:

  • The study Sponsor or representatives of the sponsor The Wellcome Trust
  • Representatives of UT Austin, such as the Institutional Review Board (IRB; a committee in charge of protecting the rights and welfare of research participants)
  • Researchers or representatives from The University of the Witswatersrand, Oxford University, De Montfort University, Zurich University of Applied Sciences, and D’Or Institute of Research and Education, who are also conducting this study.


Under certain situations, we may break confidentiality. If during the study we learn about child abuse or neglect, or that someone is a clear, serious, and direct harm to self or others, we will report this information to the appropriate authorities, including the police and/or the Texas Department of Family and Protective Services, and/or an emergency medical facility.



What will happen to the information we collect about you after the study is over?


In general, we will not give you any individual results from the study. Research data will be kept for at least 3 years after study completion. During this time, your name and other information that can directly identify you will be kept secure. 

In the future, identifiers might be removed from the information you provide in this study, and after that removal, the information could be used for other research studies by this study team or another researcher without asking you for additional consent.  


How will we compensate you for being part of the study? 


You will not receive any type of payment for your participation.


Can you stop being in the study?


You can stop being in this research study at any time. Leaving the study will not affect your medical care, employment status, or academic standing at UT Austin and/or other applicable entities. Tell the study staff if you are thinking about stopping or decide to stop.

If you decide to withdraw before this study is completed, your collected responses will be deleted.

Technological Landscape Barriers in Neuroimaging

This short (5-7 minute/27 questions max) anonymous survey is designed to help identify technical barriers to sharing human neuroimaging data (e.g., MRI, EEG, MEG, etc.). If you work with human brain data as a clinician, technician, researcher, student, or in any capacity your responses will help us guide our efforts to focus on the predominant technical issues when sharing data. Thank you!
